# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alabama-in-the-american-civil-war
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The **1804 Haiti massacre** was a genocide carried out by Afro-Haitian soldiers, mostly former slaves, under orders from Jean-Jacques Dessalines against much of the remaining European population in Haiti, which mainly included French people.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The Haitian Revolution defeated the French army in November 1803 and the Haitian Declaration of Independence happened on 1 January 1804.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] From February 1804 until 22 April 1804, between 3,000 and 7,000 people were killed.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The massacre excluded surviving Polish Legionnaires, who had defected from the French legion to become allied with the enslaved Africans, as well as the Germans who did not take part in the slave trade, and some other select whites.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] They were instead granted full citizenship under the constitution, even though Dessalines had declared that all Haitians would be considered "black".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Nicholas Robins, Adam Jones, and Dirk Moses theorize that the executions were a "subaltern genocide", in which an oppressed group uses genocidal means to destroy its oppressors.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Philippe Girard has suggested the threat of reinvasion and reinstatement of slavery as some of the reasons for the massacre.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Throughout the early-to-mid nineteenth century, the events of the massacre were well known in the United States.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Additionally, many Saint Domingue refugees moved from Saint-Domingue to the U.S., settling in New Orleans, Charleston, New York, Baltimore, and other coastal cities.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] These events spurred fears of potential uprisings in the Southern U.S. and they also polarized public opinion on the question of the abolition of slavery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In 1791, a man of Jamaican origin named Dutty Boukman became the leader of the enslaved Africans held on a large plantation in Cap-Français.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In the wake of the French Revolution, he planned to massacre all the French living in Cap-Français.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] On 22 August 1791, the enslaved Africans descended on Le Cap, where they destroyed the plantations and executed all the French who lived in the region.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] King Louis XVI was accused of indifference to the massacre, while the slaves seemed to think the king was on their side.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In July 1793, the French in Les Cayes were massacred.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Despite the French proclamation of emancipation, the blacks sided with the Spanish who came to occupy the region.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In July 1794, Spanish forces stood by while the black troops of Jean-François massacred the French whites in Fort-Dauphin.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Philippe Girard writes that genocide was openly considered as a strategy by both sides in the conflict.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] White forces sent by Napoleon Bonaparte committed massacres but were defeated before they could accomplish genocide, while an army under Jean-Jacques Dessalines, composed mainly of former slaves, was able to wipe out the white Haitian population.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines came to power after France's defeat and subsequent evacuation from what was previously known as Saint-Domingue.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In November 1803, three days after Rochambeau's forces surrendered, Dessalines ordered the execution of 800 French soldiers who had been left behind due to illness during the evacuation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] He did guarantee the safety of the remaining white civilian population.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] However, Jeremy Popkin writes that statements by Dessalines such as "There are still French on the island, and still you considered yourselves free," spoke of a hostile attitude toward the remaining white minority.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Rumors about the white population suggested that they would try to leave the country to convince foreign powers to invade and reintroduce slavery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Discussions between Dessalines and his advisers openly suggested that the white population should be put to death for the sake of national security.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Whites trying to leave Haiti were prevented from doing so.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] On 1 January 1804, Dessalines proclaimed Haiti an independent nation as the first modern independent Black republic.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In mid-February, Dessalines told some cities (Léogâne, Jacmel, Les Cayes) to prepare for mass massacres.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] On 22 February 1804, he signed a decree ordering that all whites in all cities should be put to death.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The weapons used should be silent weapons such as knives and bayonets rather than gunfire, so that the killing could be done more quietly, and avoid warning intended victims by the sound of gunfire and thereby giving them the opportunity to escape.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] During February and March, Dessalines traveled among the cities of Haiti to assure himself that his orders were carried out.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Despite his orders, the massacres were often not carried out until he visited the cities in person.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The course of the massacre showed an almost identical pattern in every city he visited.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Before his arrival, there were only a few killings, despite his orders.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] When Dessalines arrived, he first spoke about the atrocities committed by former white authorities, such as Rochambeau and Leclerc, after which he demanded that his orders about mass killings of the area's white population should be put into effect.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Reportedly, he ordered the unwilling to take part in the killings, especially men of mixed race, so that the blame should not be placed solely on the black population.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Mass killings took place on the streets and on places outside the cities.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In Port-au-Prince, only a few killings had occurred in the city despite the orders.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] After Dessalines arrived on 18 March, the number of killings escalated.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] According to a merchant captain, about 800 people were killed in the city, while about 50 survived.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] On 18 April 1804, Dessalines arrived at Cap-Haïtien.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Only a handful of killings had taken place there before his arrival, but the killings escalated to a massacre on the streets and outside the city after his arrival.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Sources created at the time stated that 3,000 people were killed in Cap-Haïtien; Philippe Girard writes that this figure was unrealistic as in the post-evacuation of the French people the settlement had only 1,700 white people.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Before his departure from a city, Dessalines would proclaim an amnesty for all the whites who had survived in hiding during the massacre.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] When these people left their hiding place however, most (French) were killed as well.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Many whites were, however, hidden and smuggled out to sea by foreigners.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] However, there were notable exceptions to the ordered killings.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] A contingent of Polish defectors were given amnesty and granted Haitian citizenship for their renouncement of French allegiance and support of Haitian independence.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines referred to the Poles as *"the White Negroes of Europe"*, as an expression of his solidarity and gratitude.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] According to historian Julia Gaffield, most of those killed were former members of the National Guard, a pro-French militia.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The French, who were one of the two main targets of the 1804 Haiti Massacre that Dessalines and his company specifically declared a massacre on, made up the overwhelming majority of the white population.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The white victims were almost entirely French, commensurate with their share in the white population of Haiti.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] During the massacre, stabbing, beheading, and disemboweling were common.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In parallel to the killings, plundering and rape also occurred.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] As elsewhere, the majority of the women were initially not killed, and the soldiers were reportedly somewhat hesitant to do so.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines's advisers, however, pointed out that the white Haitians would not disappear if the women were left to give birth to white men, and after this, Dessalines ordered that the women should be killed as well, with the exception of those who agreed to marry non-white men.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] One of the most notorious of the massacre participants was Jean Zombi, a mulatto resident of Port-au-Prince who was known for his brutality.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] One account describes how Zombi stopped a white man on the street, stripped him naked, and took him to the stair of the Presidential Palace, where he killed him with a dagger.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines was reportedly among the spectators; he was said to be "horrified" by the episode.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In Haitian Vodou tradition, the figure of Jean Zombi has become a prototype for the zombie.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] At the conclusion of the slaughter, Dessalines reportedly stated: "I will go to my grave happy.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] By the end of April 1804, some 3,000 to 5,000 people had been killed and the white Haitians were practically eradicated, excluding a select group of whites who were given amnesty.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Those spared consisted of the Polish ex-soldiers who were given Haitian citizenship for helping black Haitians in fights against white colonialists; a small group of German colonists invited to the north-west region before the revolution; and a group of medical doctors and professionals.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Reportedly, also people with connections to officers in the Haitian army were spared, as well as the women who agreed to marry non-white men.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines did not try to hide the massacre from the world.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In an official proclamation of 8 April 1804, he stated, "We have given these true cannibals war for war, crime for crime, outrage for outrage.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Yes, I have saved my country, I have avenged America." He referred to the massacre as an act of national authority.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines regarded the elimination of the white Haitians an act of political necessity, as they were regarded as a threat to the peace between the black and the free people of color.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] It was also regarded as a necessary act of vengeance.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Dessalines was eager to assure that Haiti was not a threat to other nations.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] He directed efforts to establish friendly relations also to nations where slavery was still allowed.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In the 1805 constitution, all citizens were defined as "black".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The constitution also banned white men from owning land, except for people already born or born in the future to white women who were naturalized as Haitian citizens and the Germans and Poles who got Haitian citizenship.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The massacre had a long-lasting effect on the view of the Haitian Revolution.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] It contributed to a legacy of racial hostility in Haitian society.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Girard writes in his book *Paradise Lost*: "Despite all of Dessalines' efforts at rationalization, the massacres were as inexcusable as they were foolish." Trinidadian historian C.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] James concurred with this view in his breakthrough work *The Black Jacobins*, writing that "the unfortunate country... was ruined economically, its population lacking in social culture, [and] had its difficulties doubled by this massacre".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] James wrote that the massacre was "not policy but revenge, and revenge has no place in politics".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Philippe Girard wrote that "when the genocide was over, Haiti's white population was virtually non-existent." Citing Girard, Nicholas Robins, and Adam Jones describe the massacre as a "subaltern genocide" in which a previously disadvantaged group used a genocide to destroy their previous oppressors.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] At the time of the American Civil War, a major pretext for Southern whites, most of whom did not own slaves, to support slave owners (and ultimately fight for the Confederacy) was fear of a genocide similar to the Haitian massacre of 1804.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The perceived failure of abolition in Haiti and Jamaica were explicitly referred to in Confederate discourse as a reason for secession.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The slave revolt was a prominent theme in the discourse of Southern political leaders and had influenced U.S. public opinion since the events took place.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In the run-up to the U.S. presidential election of 1860, Roger B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Taney, Chief Justice of the Supreme Court, wrote "I remember the horrors of St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Abolitionists recognized the strength of this argument on public opinion in both the North and South.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] In correspondence to the *New York Times* in September 1861 (during the war), an abolitionist named J.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Lyon argued, however, that the abolition of slavery in the various Caribbean colonies of the European empires before the 1860s showed that an end to slavery could be achieved peacefully.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Girard writes that the 1804 massacres must be understood in their specific, Haitian context.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] He classifies the massacres as a genocide, and contrasts them with their historical counterparts.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] The Haitian massacres "lack the moral clarity typically associated with genocide," he says, because the French colonists had abused Black Haitians and would have carried out their own genocide had they won the conflict.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1804-haiti-massacre] Girard also contrasts the overt nature of the Haitian massacres and the willingness of leadership to take responsibility for and justify the massacres with the diffusion and obfuscation of responsibility by both rank and file participants and leaders in other genocides.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1864, near the end of the American Civil War.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President Abraham Lincoln of the National Union Party easily defeated the Democratic nominee, former General George B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, by a wide margin of 212–21 in the electoral college, with 55% of the popular vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For the election, the Republican Party and some Democrats created the National Union Party, especially to attract War Democrats.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite some intra-party opposition from Salmon Chase and the Radical Republicans, Lincoln won his party's nomination at the 1864 National Union National Convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than re-nominate Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, the convention selected Andrew Johnson of Tennessee, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were divided between the Copperheads, who favored immediate peace with the Confederacy, and War Democrats, who supported the war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 Democratic National Convention nominated McClellan, a War Democrat, but adopted a platform advocating peace with the Confederacy, which McClellan rejected, although his running mate George H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] While the Confederacy seemed to have survival potential in summer 1864, it was visibly collapsing by election day in November.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his early fears of defeat, Lincoln won strong majorities in the popular and electoral vote, partly as a result of the recent Union victory at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War was still raging, no electoral votes were counted from any of the eleven southern states that had joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's re-election ensured that he would preside over the successful conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's victory made him the first president to win re-election since Andrew Jackson in 1832, as well as the first Northern president to ever win re-election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was assassinated six weeks into his second term.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was succeeded by his vice president, Andrew Johnson, who favored quick restoration of the seceded states to the Union without protection for the former slaves.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This led to conflict with the Republican-dominated Congress, culminating in Johnson's impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1868; he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election took place during the American Civil War.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] According to the Miller Center for the study of the presidency, the election was noteworthy for occurring at all, an unprecedented democratic exercise in the midst of a civil war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Republican dissidents who called themselves Radical Republicans formed a party named the Radical Democratic Party and nominated John C.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont as their candidate for president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont later withdrew and endorsed Lincoln.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] War Democrats joined with Republicans as the National Union Party, with Lincoln at the head of the ticket.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The National Union Party was a temporary name used to attract War Democrats and Southern Border State Unionists who would not vote for the Republican Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It faced off against the regular Democratic Party, including Peace Democrats.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election conventions of the parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War progressed, political opinions within the Republican Party began to diverge.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Senators Charles Sumner and Henry Wilson from Massachusetts wanted the Republican Party to advocate constitutional amendments to prohibit slavery and guarantee racial equality before the law.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, not all northern Republicans supported such measures.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders hoped that the radical Republicans would put forth their own ticket in the election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* newspaper, particularly interested in undermining the National Union Party, ran a series of articles predicting a delay for the National Union Convention until late in 1864 to allow Frémont time to collect delegates to win the nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont supporters in New York City established a newspaper called the *New Nation*, which declared in one of its initial issues that the National Union Convention would be a "nonentity".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* also published false information (further purported by Samuel S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Before the election, some War Democrats joined the Republicans to form the National Union Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With the outcome of the Civil War still in doubt, some political leaders, including Salmon P.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase, Benjamin Wade, and Horace Greeley, opposed Lincoln's re-nomination on the grounds that he could not win.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase himself became the only candidate to contest Lincoln's re-nomination actively, but he withdrew in March when a slew of Republican officials, including some within the state of Ohio upon whom Chase's campaign depended, endorsed Lincoln for re-nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was still popular with most members of the Republican Party, and the National Union Party nominated him for a second term as president at their convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on June 7–8, 1864.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent vice president Hannibal Hamlin remaining indifferent about the prospect of a second term in office, Andrew Johnson, the former senator from and current military governor of Tennessee, was named as Lincoln's vice presidential running-mate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He had been governor of Tennessee from 1853 to 1857 and was elected by the legislature to the Senate in 1857.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat in 1862.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern slave states, including Tennessee, seceded, he remained firmly with the Union.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was the only sitting senator from a Confederate state who did not resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as military governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1864, Johnson was a logical choice as running mate for Lincoln, who wished to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign, especially to ensure the electoral votes of the border states.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Others who were considered for the nomination, at one point or another, were former Senator Daniel Dickinson, Major General Benjamin Butler, Major General William Rosecrans, Joseph Holt, and former Treasury Secretary and Senator John Dix.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was bitterly split between War Democrats and Peace Democrats, a group further divided among competing factions.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Moderate Peace Democrats who supported the war against the Confederacy, such as Horatio Seymour, were preaching the wisdom of a negotiated peace.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After the Union victory at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, moderate Peace Democrats proposed a negotiated peace that would secure Union victory.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They believed this was the best course of action, because an armistice could finish the war without devastating the South.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Radical Peace Democrats known as Copperheads, such as Thomas H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Seymour, declared the war to be a failure and favored an immediate end to hostilities without securing Union victory.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan vied for the presidential nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, friends of Horatio Seymour insisted on placing his name before the convention, which was held in Chicago, Illinois, on August 29–31, 1864.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] But on the day before the organization of that body, Horatio Seymour announced positively that he would not be a candidate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Since the Democrats were divided by issues of war and peace, they sought a strong candidate who could unify the party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The compromise was to nominate pro-war General George B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan for president and anti-war Representative George H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, a War Democrat, was nominated for president over the Copperhead Thomas H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Pendleton, a close associate of the Copperhead Clement Vallandigham, balanced the ticket, since he was known for having strongly opposed the Union war effort.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention adopted a peace platform – a platform McClellan personally rejected.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan supported the continuation of the war and restoration of the Union, but the party platform, written by Vallandigham, opposed this position.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Radical Democratic Convention assembled in Ohio with delegates arriving on May 29, 1864.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] *The New York Times* reported that the hall which the convention organizers had planned to use had been double-booked by an opera troupe.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Almost all delegates were instructed to support Frémont, with a major exception being the New York delegation, which was composed of War Democrats who supported Ulysses S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Various estimates of the number of delegates were reported in the press; *The New York Times* reported 156 delegates, but the number generally reported elsewhere was 350 delegates.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates came from 15 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They adopted the name Radical Democratic Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A supporter of Grant was appointed chairman.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The platform was passed with little discussion, and a series of resolutions that bogged down the convention proceedings were voted down decisively.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Frémont for president, and he accepted the nomination on June 4, 1864.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his letter, he stated that he would step aside if the National Union Convention would nominate someone other than Lincoln for president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] John Cochrane was nominated for vice president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 election was the first time since 1812 that a presidential election took place during a war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For much of 1864, Lincoln himself believed he had little chance of being re-elected.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Confederate forces had triumphed at the Battle of Mansfield, the Battle of Cold Harbor, the Battle of Brices Cross Roads, the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain and the Battle of the Crater.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the war was continuing to take a very high toll in terms of casualties with campaigns such as Grant's Overland Campaign and the perceived lack of progress.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of a long and bloody war started to make the idea of "peace at all cost" offered by the Ultra Peace Democrats look more desirable.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] However, several political and military events eventually made Lincoln's re-election inevitable.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the first place, the Democrats had to confront the severe internal strains within their party at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The political compromises made at the Democratic National Convention were contradictory and made McClellan's efforts to campaign seem inconsistent.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Secondly, the Democratic National Convention influenced Frémont's campaign.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was appalled at the Democratic platform, which he described as "union with slavery".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After three weeks of discussions with Cochrane and his supporters, Frémont withdrew from the race in September 1864.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his statement, Frémont declared that winning the Civil War was too important to divide the Republican vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Although he still felt that Lincoln was not going far enough, the defeat of McClellan was of the greatest necessity.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] General Cochrane, who was a War Democrat, agreed and withdrew with Frémont.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, 1864, Frémont also brokered a political deal in which Lincoln removed U.S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Montgomery Blair from office, and on September 24 Abraham Lincoln relieved Blair of his duty as Postmaster General.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan's chances of victory faded after Frémont withdrew from the presidential race.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lastly, with the fall of Atlanta on September 2, there was no longer any question that a Union military victory was inevitable and close at hand.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Union Party mobilized the full strength of both the Republicans and the War Democrats under the slogan "Don't change horses in the middle of a stream".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It was energized as Lincoln made emancipation the central issue, and state Republican parties stressed the perfidy of the Copperheads.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] 24.4% of the voting age population and 76.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The American Civil War was in progress and unfinished during this election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Because eleven Southern states plus two claimed additional Southern states had declared secession from the Union and formed the Confederate States of America, only twenty-five states participated in the election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Louisiana and Tennessee had recently been re-captured.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They chose presidential electors, but their votes were rejected by Congress due to having recently seceded from the Union.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Both states had voted for Lincoln, so it would not have changed the result in any case.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Three new states participated for the first time: Kansas, West Virginia, and Nevada.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan won just three states: Kentucky, Delaware, and his home state of New Jersey.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln won in every state he carried in 1860 except New Jersey, and also carried a state won four years earlier by Stephen Douglas (Missouri), one carried by John C.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge (Maryland) and all three newly admitted states (Kansas, Nevada and West Virginia).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Altogether, 212 electoral votes were counted in Congress for Lincoln – more than enough to win the presidency even if all of the states in rebellion had participated and voted against him.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the last election in which a party nominee won completely different states than the previous nominee, with McClellan flipping Kentucky and New Jersey, while having lost Missouri.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was highly popular with soldiers and they in turn recommended him to their families back home.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The following states allowed soldiers to cast ballots: California, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Rhode Island, and Wisconsin.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Only soldiers from Kentucky gave McClellan a majority of their votes, and he carried the army vote in the state by a vote of 2,823 (70.3%) to 1,194 (29.7%).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,129 counties making returns, Lincoln won in 728 (64.5%), while McClellan carried 400 (35.4%).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.1%) in Iowa split evenly between Lincoln and McClellan.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election the Republicans won in Maryland until 1896.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The states in rebellion did not participate in the election of 1864.* (b) *The 17 electoral votes from Tennessee and Louisiana were rejected.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1864-united-states-presidential-election] States in red were won by Republican Abraham Lincoln; states in blue were won by Democrat George B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation was launched before the adjournment of the trial and continued after the trial adjourned on May 26, 1868.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The leading figure of the investigation was Benjamin Butler.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The final report of the investigation was published on July 3, 1868.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On February 21, 1868, in disregard for the Tenure of Office Act, Andrew Johnson (the president of the United States) attempted to replace Edwin Stanton (the United States secretary of war) with Lorenzo Thomas.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This led the United States House of Representatives, on February 24, to impeach Johnson.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After the impeachment, an impeachment trial began in the United States Senate where the Senate would judge whether to convict Johnson, thereby removing him from office.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While the investigation never proved bribery, there is evidence of efforts by both those supporting the prosecution and the defense having made offers to senators to persuade their votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This includes evidence of promises of patronage jobs, cash bribes, and political dealmaking being made to solicit votes for acquittal.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There is evidence that the prosecution may have attempted to bribe the senators voting for acquittal to switch their votes to conviction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Aspects of this possible scheme were partially uncovered by the investigation, but it was never proven by the investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] All of the individuals, except for Wooley, had ties to United States Secretary of State William H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Seward, who also appears implicated in this scheme.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Evidence also suggests that Alexander Randall and Edmund Cooper (a leader at the United States Department of the Treasury) were possibly in charge of managing an "acquittal fund" for Johnson.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On May 16, 1868, the Senate voted against convicting Johnson on the eleventh article of impeachment, which had been considered the article with the strongest chance of securing a conviction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It fell one vote shy of the two-thirds needed for impeachment, with the vote to convict being 32–21.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After this, the Senate voted to adjourn the trial and reconvene to resume voting on the remaining ten articles of impeachment on March 26, 1868.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This resolution had been justified by the impeachment managers with the claim that information had been provided to them that provided them with probable cause to suspect improper or corrupt means had influenced the Senate vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After the resolution passed, a subcommittee was created and began hearing testimony during the hiatus.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation that subsequently unfolded proved relatively extreme and unconstrained.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The leading force of the investigation was Benjamin Butler (R– MA).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers, during the hiatus between votes, began searching for possible corrupt means that may have persuaded senators to acquit.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation took a heavy-handed prosecutorial approach, subpoenaing telegrams, and looking into the bank accounts of private citizens that just-so happened to have withdrawn large amounts.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler was confident that votes had been bought by Johnson allies, and wanted to prove it.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The effort was disparaged as a "smelling committee" by Democrats and some of the press.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Many Republicans were also dubious towards the investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While there is substantial evidence to suggest that there were several senators that voted to convict who Johnson could likely have counted on to vote for an acquittal had their votes been needed, only those who actually voted to convict were the focus of the impeachment managers' investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the telegrams found were a number that seemed incriminating.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Hours before the vote on May 16 to acquit, Charles Woolley sent Congressman George H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pendleton (D– OH) a telegram reading, "Andy all right." Many witnesses testified that they had heard talk of vote-purchasing, but many of these witnesses were also unable to recall who they heard it from or greater details about what they had heard.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Within hours of the authorization of the investigation, the impeachment managers had subpoenaed eight witnesses, including Senator Edmund G.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross (who had voted to acquit), Perry Fuller (an Indian trader and a political fixer), and several individuals from Missouri that had tried unsuccessfully to convince John B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] That evening, the committee began hearing testimony, with their first witness being Senator Ross' brother William, who expressed disappointment in his brother's vote but denied any knowledge of corruption in the Senate vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers received a large number of tips from people around the country of leads they should pursue.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, the individual who had Butler's ear the most with his advice on this was *National Police Gazette*-publisher George Wilkes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes' newspaper was known to scandalmonger.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes had a secret informant that was close to Samuel Ward (a notable lobbyist).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This source reported that Ward had paid Senator Edmund G.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross for his vote to acquit with $12,000 from Democratic congressman John Morrissey.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes speculated that the transfer of money was handled by "Charley Morgan", who was a cross-dresser who was allegedly involved in separate extramarital affairs with both Morrissey's wife and Samuel Ward.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During the middle of the investigation, a young woman going by the name "Charley Morgan" was arrested in New York, pleading guilty to a misdemeanor charge of "indecency" for crossdressing.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] She told the court that she had gone four years without wearing women's clothing.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler, however, gave assurances to Ward that this was not his doing, pointing to the fact that he had gone against pressure to embarrass Ward by calling her as a witness in the investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler would never find proof that Ward had bribed Ross.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation included a focus on a number of Johnson-allied figures, including Thurlow Weed and Charles Woolley.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Thurlow Weed told the committee that there had been a group that was determined to secure Johnson's acquittal.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Smythe was an individual that had been accused of corruption in the past, and had previously nearly been ejected from office as a result.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Weed also said that it included Sheridan Shook, former congressman Samuel S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During the investigation, there was evidence found that United States Secretary of State William Seward and Postmaster General Alexander Randall had been in contact with Cornelius Wendell (a Washington printer) for the purposes of organizing bribes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wendell told the committee that he had been uninterested in being part of this plan, and pointed blame on Seward's aide Erastus Webster, who it appeared had collected a fund of $165,000 for the purposes of buying acquittal votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This money was said to have primarily been raised by Randall, Hugh McCulloch (United States secretary of the treasury) and Henry A.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Smythe through middlemen such as Perry Fuller and James Legate (a special agent of the Kansas Post Office Department), though Fuller and Legate were said to have pocketed most of the money raised for themselves.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wendell also testified about Charles Woolley's alleged involvement.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] James Legate testified that Perry Fuller had told him that, if impeachment failed, Salmon Chase (the chief Justice of the United States, who acted as the trial's presiding officer) would run a third-party campaign for the presidency.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He also said that the raising of money for a potential Chase presidential bid was being used as a front for establishing a fund to support the acquittal of Johnson.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the other individuals interviewed was Thomas Ewing Jr.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Much evidence implicated Senator Samuel C.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pomeroy, who had voted to convict, in possible corruption.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler attempted to ignore this evidence, however.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation uncovered evidence that there had been discussions of bribes for votes to convict.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was discovered during the investigation that Kansas Senator Pomeroy, who voted for conviction, had written a letter to Johnson's postmaster general seeking a $40,000 bribe for Pomeroy's acquittal vote along with three or four others in his caucus.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley became a central focus of Butler's from the first day of the trial.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers sought to hear from Woolley, who kept giving changing excuses for inability to come before them.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the matters they had questions for Woolley about was $10,000 that he had received from Sheridan Shook, a deputy collector of internal revenue in New York.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley had withdrawn the money in $1,000 bills, which drew suspicion.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] When he appeared himself, Shook answered very few questions in his testimony before the committee, and many of his answers were seen as nonsensical.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Other witnesses on this matter had feigned ignorance or had been otherwise evasive in their answers to questions.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ordway (the sergeant at arms of the House) took custody of Woolley and brought him before the House on March 26.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, Woolley's appearance was interrupted that day by a recess so that congressmen could attend the Senate impeachment trial vote that day.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The committee submitted a report on their preliminary findings on May 26, hours before the Senate met again to vote on articles of impeachment.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While some senators attempted to get the trial to adjourn until the end of June to allow the impeachment managers more time to investigate before the vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This was rejected because few others believed that the allegations could be proven.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The Senate voted identically on the second and third articles of impeachment, again by 32–21 votes before voting to adjourn sine die.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On March 26, 1868, after the trial adjourned, the House voted 91–30 to approve a resolution presented by Benjamin Butler authorizing the House impeachment managers to continue this investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler led the continuation of the investigation and conducted hearings and inquiry into widespread reports that Republican senators had been bribed to vote for Johnson's acquittal.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On March 26, shortly after the Senate trial adjourned, the impeachment managers returned to question Charles Woolley.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He failed to cooperate with their questioning, refusing to answer questions that he asserted were unrelated to the trial.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This included questions about what he had done with $10,000 that he had received from a deputy collector of internal revenue in New York named Sheridan Shook.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After this, House voted 60–51 that day to hold him in contempt of Congress and had him held in custody by the sergeant at arms of the House.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He was first kept in the House Committee on Foreign Affairs' hearing room, but, as his arrest grew in length, he was later moved to the basement room that Vinnie Ream had been utilizing as a sculpture studio, forcing the artist to move her work into the hallway.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Conservatives charged that Benjamin Butler was intentionally targeting Ream in his successful resolution to turn her studio into a Capitol Police guardroom.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley's arrest attracted great media attention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] When Woolley was questioned on May 27, he was denied a request for a lawyer.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler found him still inadequately responsive to questions, and sent him back to his holding cell.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The final report Butler wrote doubted this, calling it a, "stupid fabrication".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Eleven days later, Woolley told that house he would answer Butler's questions, and Butler questioned him again.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Van Valkenberg came before the committee again, with $17,000 of cash and accompanied by a hotel manager who told the impeachment managers that this money had indeed been in a hotel safe.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was impossible to prove whether this was Woolley's money or not.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After he appeared before the investigative committee and answered their questions to an extent that they found satisfactory, the House voted to discharge Woolley from their custody on June 11, 1868.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers took testimony for a total of six weeks the May 16 authorization of their investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In some instances, Butler individually interrogated witnesses.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During these six weeks, Butler had detectives search for proof of bribery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There was some speculation that Butler was motivated by a desire to not be blamed himself for the failure to secure a conviction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was rumored, however, that Butler hidden thirty-six volumes of incriminating telegrams in hopes he could later use them to blackmail congressional colleagues in the future.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was also rumored that Butler had offered $100,000 to Cornelius Wendell in exchange for information, but had suppressed evidence of this offer.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In the post-trial hearings and investigations there was growing evidence that some acquittal votes were acquired by promises of patronage jobs and cash bribes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Grimes received assurances that acquittal would not be followed by presidential reprisals; Johnson agreed to enforce the Reconstruction Acts, and to appoint General John Schofield to succeed Stanton.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Nonetheless, the investigations never resulted in charges, much less convictions, against anyone.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation also boomeranged by uncovering evidence that there had been discussions of bribes for vote to covict.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Democrats were not worried by the investigation, and came to see it as amusing due to Butler's failure to find hard evidence of bribery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was reported that the impeachment managers had testimony showing implications of bribery, but did not provide solid evidence of bribery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In contrast the strictness that Woolley had faced, the impeachment managers were more lax when it came to the testimony of some witnesses.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] A number of witnesses were allowed to decline to answer questions, be evasive, or contradict evidence without consequence.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Some witnesses faced informal questioning that was not under oath.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Samuel Ward smoked cigars with Butler after he testified before the committee for two hours.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Adams, being questioned for allegedly originating a bribery scheme, gave what the impeachment managers found to be an "utterly false and untruthful" claim by declaring he could not recall at what time he had become a general, Butler did not pursue any action against him.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler, perhaps, was selective with what truths he sought to uncover in the investigation, hoping only to find those that would harm the president and the Democratic Party and help the Republicans.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Even when it came to matters he wanted to uncover, Butler appears to have been selective in which leads he chose to follow, disregarding some leads more that were potentially promising than the ones he chose to follow.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Fowler as having been bribed for his vote against impeachment.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Seven congressmen gave a statement that, in January 1868, Fowler had demanded the impeachment of Johnson.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Henderson, who had promised to vote to convict on the eleventh article four days before he voted to acquit on it.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There is historical evidence that Perry Fuller had bribed Senator Ross.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, Butler never managed to prove this act of bribery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Fuller admitted that, at the authority of Edmund Cooper, he had offered $40,000 to Senator Samuel C.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pomeroy's brother-in-law Willis Gaylord.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In late-May 1868, amid the investigation, he acknowledged having paid for the outstanding expense of the home mortgage of James Legate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It appears that Legate had also given Fuller his records of the bribery scheme, and that Fuller had burned them.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Historical evidence shows that Fuller had admitted to doing so in hopes of, "drying up the investigation".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Being unable to definitively prove that bribery took place, Butler wrote a final report on the evidence found and testimony taken by the impeachment managers in their investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler rushedly published the final report of the investigation on July 3, 1868.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He hoped that this would hurt Johnson's prospects at the Democratic Party's presidential nomination at the 1868 Democratic National Convention held in New York City the following week.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Senators suspected of selling their acquittal votes attacked the report on the Senate floor.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross attacked what he called Butler's, "well-known groveling instincts and proness to slime and uncleanness".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Eighteen months after the end of the trial, journalist Henry V.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Boynton published an investigative news report that sought to tie up loose ends in Butler's investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He identified three different alleged bribery schemes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Boynton was unhappy with Butler's handling of the impeachment managers' investigation, believing his pursuit of Woolley had been to the detriment of pursuing other guilty parties.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He was also angered by Butler's failure to publish important testimony from the investigation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Cornelius Wendell gave a news interview that confirmed aspects of Boynton's reporting, and which accused Perry Fuller of offering Senator Ross several thousand dollars to influence his vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Few transcripts of testimony from the investigation survive.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 4, 1884.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic Governor Grover Cleveland of New York narrowly defeated Republican James G.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine of Maine, ending a streak of four consecutive Republican victories.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Cleveland won the presidential nomination on the second ballot of the 1884 Democratic National Convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Arthur had acceded to the presidency in 1881 following the assassination of James A.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield, but he was unsuccessful in his bid for nomination to a full term.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine, who had served as Secretary of State under President Garfield, defeated Arthur and other candidates on the fourth ballot of the 1884 Republican National Convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] A group of reformist Republicans known as "Mugwumps" abandoned Blaine's candidacy, viewing him as corrupt.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was characterized by mudslinging and personal allegations that eclipsed substantive issues, such as civil administration change, and it was marred by exceptional political acrimony and personal invective.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine's reputation for public corruption and his inadvertent last minute alienation of Catholic voters proved decisive, as well as voter exhaustion after a generation of Republican rule.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] In the election, Cleveland won 48.8% of the nationwide popular vote and 219 electoral votes, carrying the Solid South and several key swing states.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine won 48.3% of the popular vote and 182 electoral votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Cleveland won his home state by just 1,149 votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] John of the Prohibition Party and Benjamin Butler of the Greenback Party and the Anti-Monopoly Party, each won less than 2% of the popular vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine became the only Republican nominee in the 52-year period from 1860 to 1912 never to win a presidential election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] He was also the last former secretary of state to be nominated by a major political party until 2016.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] This election was also the last time there would be two consecutive presidential elections without an incumbent president on the ballot until 2028.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats convened in Chicago on July 8–11, 1884, with New York Governor Grover Cleveland as clear frontrunner, the candidate of northern reformers and sound-money men (as opposed to inflationists).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Although Tammany Hall bitterly opposed his nomination, the machine represented a minority of the New York delegation.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Its only chance to block Cleveland was to break the unit rule, which mandated that the votes of an entire delegation be cast for only one candidate, and this it failed to do.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Lockwood from New York placed Cleveland's name in nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] But this rather lackluster address was eclipsed by the seconding speech of Edward S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Bragg from Wisconsin, who roused the delegates with a memorable slap at Tammany.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] On the first ballot, Cleveland led the field with 392 votes, more than 150 votes short of the nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Randall from Pennsylvania, 78; and Joseph E.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] McDonald from Indiana, 56; with the rest scattered.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Randall then withdrew in Cleveland's favor.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] This move, together with the Southern bloc scrambling aboard the Cleveland bandwagon, was enough to put him over the top of the second ballot, with 683 votes to 81.5 for Bayard and 45.5 for Thomas A.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Hendricks was nominated unanimously for vice president on the first ballot after John C.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Black, William Rosecrans, and George Washington Glick withdrew their names from consideration.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The 1884 Republican National Convention was held in Chicago, Illinois, on June 3–6, with former Secretary of State James G.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine from Maine, President Arthur, and Senator George F.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Edmunds from Vermont as the frontrunners.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Though he was still popular, Arthur did not make a serious bid for a full-term nomination, knowing that his increasing health problems meant he would probably not survive a second term (he ultimately died in November 1886).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine led on the first ballot, with Arthur second, and Edmunds third.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] This order did not change on successive ballots as Blaine increased his lead, and he won a majority on the fourth ballot.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] After nominating Blaine, the convention chose Senator John A.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Logan from Illinois as the vice-presidential nominee.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine remains the only presidential nominee ever to come from Maine.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The Anti-Monopoly National Convention assembled in the Hershey Music Hall in Chicago, Illinois on May 14.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The party had been formed to express opposition to the business practices of the emerging nationwide companies.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] There were around 200 delegates from 16 states, but 61 of them were from Michigan and Illinois.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Alson Streeter was the temporary chairman and John F.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Benjamin Butler was nominated for president on the first ballot.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from New York, Washington, D.C., and Maryland bolted the convention when it appeared that no discussion of other candidates would be allowed.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver were put forward as alternatives to Butler, but Weaver declined, not wishing to run another national campaign for political office, and Thurman generated little enthusiasm.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Butler, while far from opposed to the nomination, hoped to be nominated by the Democratic or Republican party, or at least in the case of the former, to make its platform more favorable to greenbacks.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Ultimately only the Greenback Party endorsed his candidacy.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The convention chose not to nominate a candidate for vice president, hoping that other conventions would endorse a similar platform and name a suitable vice-presidential nominee.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The committee ultimately nominated Absolom Madden West as their vice-presidential candidate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The third Greenback National Convention assembled in English's Opera House in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from 28 states and the District of Columbia were in attendance.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated former Massachusetts Governor Benjamin Butler for president over party chairman Jesse Harper on the first ballot.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] West was nominated unanimously for vice president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The ticket was subsequently adopted by the Anti-Monopoly Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Butler initially hoped to organize fusion tickets with the minority party in each state, a strategy designed to capitalize on the cross-partisan popularity of many elements of the candidate's program.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The Greenbacks succeeded in negotiating fusion arrangements with the Democrats in Iowa, Michigan, and Nebraska and with the Republicans in Missouri and West Virginia.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The fusion electors agreed to divide their votes between Butler and Cleveland, or Butler and Blaine, in proportion to the statewide popular vote for each candidate; however, the fusion ticket was not elected in any state, and Butler received no votes in the Electoral College.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The American Prohibition Party held its national convention in the YMCA building in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] There were 150 delegates, including many non-voting delegates.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The party sought to merge the reform movements of anti-masonry, prohibition, anti-polygamy, and direct election of the president into a new party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Jonathan Blanchard was a major figure within the party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] During the convention, the party name was changed from the American Party to the American Prohibition Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The party had been known as the Anti-Masonic Party in 1880.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the delegates at the convention were initially interested in nominating John St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] John, the former governor of Kansas, but it was feared that such a nomination might cost him that of the Prohibition Party, which he was actively seeking.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Pomeroy, a former senator from the same state who was the convention's runner-up for the nomination, and at Pomeroy's suggestion they agreed to withdraw the ticket from the race should St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] John win the Prohibition Party nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] John later unanimously won the Prohibition Party nomination, with Pomeroy and Conant withdrawing from the presidential contest and endorsing him.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York Times* speculated that the endorsement would "give him 40,000 votes".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The fourth Prohibition Party National Convention assembled in Lafayette Hall, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] There were 505 delegates from 31 states and territories at the convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The national ticket was nominated unanimously: John St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] John for president and William Daniel for vice president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The straightforward single-issue Prohibition Party platform advocated the criminalization of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Dissatisfied with resistance by the men of the major parties to women's suffrage, a small group of women announced the formation in 1884 of the Equal Rights Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The Equal Rights Party held its national convention in San Francisco, California, on September 20.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Belva Ann Lockwood, an attorney in Washington, D.C., for president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Chairman Marietta Stow, the first woman to preside over a national nominating convention, was nominated for vice president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Lockwood agreed to be the party's presidential candidate even though most women in the United States did not yet have the right to vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] She said, "I cannot vote but I can be voted for." She was the first woman to run a full campaign for the office (Victoria Woodhull conducted a more limited campaign in 1872).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The Equal Rights Party had no treasury, but Lockwood gave lectures to pay for campaign travel.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] She received approximately 4,194 votes nationally.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The issue of personal character was paramount in the 1884 campaign.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats and anti-Blaine Republicans made unrestrained attacks on his integrity as a result.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Cleveland, on the other hand, was known as "Grover the Good" for his personal integrity; in the space of the three previous years he had become successively the mayor of Buffalo, New York, and then the governor of the state of New York, cleaning up large amounts of Tammany Hall's graft.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Commentator Jeff Jacoby notes that, "Not since George Washington had a candidate for president been so renowned for his rectitude." In July the Republicans found a refutation buried in Cleveland's past.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Aided by sermons from a minister named George H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Ball, they charged that Cleveland had fathered an illegitimate child while he was a lawyer in Buffalo.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Republican cartoonists across the land had a field day.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Cleveland's campaign decided that candor was the best approach to this scandal: it admitted that Cleveland had formed an "illicit connection" with the mother and that a child had been born and given the Cleveland surname.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] They also noted that there was no proof that Cleveland was the father, and claimed that, by assuming responsibility and finding a home for the child, he was merely doing his duty.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Finally, they showed that the mother had not been forced into an asylum; her whereabouts were unknown.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The greatest threat to the Republicans came from reformers called "Mugwumps" who were angrier at Blaine's public corruption than at Cleveland's private affairs.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] In the final week of the campaign, the Blaine campaign suffered a catastrophe.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] At a Republican meeting attended by Blaine, a group of New York preachers castigated the Mugwumps.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The statement energized the Irish and Catholic vote in New York City heavily against Blaine, costing him New York state and the election by a narrow margin.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] In addition to Burchard's statement, it is also believed that John St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] John's campaign was responsible for winning Cleveland the election in New York.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Since Prohibitionists tended to ally more with Republicans, the Republican Party attempted to convince St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] When they failed, they resorted to slandering him.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, he redoubled his efforts in upstate New York, where Blaine was vulnerable on his prohibition stance, and took votes away from the Republicans.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Republican turnout in upstate New York was hampered by heavy rains.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] 35.6% of the voting age population and 78.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] While the results remained broadly the same as those from 1880, Cleveland narrowly won three states (New York, Indiana, and Connecticut) that James A.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield had won, while Blaine won two states (California and Nevada) that Winfield Hancock had won.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] But most of those states had relatively small numbers of electoral votes, and Cleveland's victory in New York was decisive.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Cleveland won by a slightly larger margin than Garfield (0.57% compared to 0.11%) in the popular vote, but a slightly smaller margin in the Electoral College (29 votes to 59).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Cleveland became the first Democrat to ever win without Pennsylvania, California, Nevada, and Illinois.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Pennsylvania voted for the losing candidate for the first time since 1824, and the loser of the popular vote since 1800.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The result marked an electoral breakthrough for the Prohibition Party, who had been little more than a fringe party in the previous three elections.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] By contrast, Butler earned less than half the popular vote share that James B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver had won in 1880, accelerating the decline of the Greenback Party.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last presidential election the party contested; it collapsed after failing to nominate a ticket in 1888.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] This election was one of only four U.S. presidential elections, held since the Democrats and Republicans became the two major parties in U.S. politics, in which the winner did not carry any of the three Rust Belt states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin; the others were 1916, 2000, and 2004.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] 16.08% of Blaine's votes came from the eleven states of the former Confederacy, with him taking 40.15% of the vote in that region.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] In Burke County, Georgia, 895 votes were cast for bolting "Whig Republican" electors for president (they were not counted for Blaine).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans won in 20 of the 33 cities with populations over 50,000 outside the southern U.S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1884-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–57.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The **1913 Gettysburg reunion** was a Gettysburg Battlefield encampment of American Civil War veterans for the Battle of Gettysburg's 50th anniversary.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The June 29 – July 4 gathering of 53,407 veterans (about 8,750 Confederate) was the largest Civil War veteran reunion.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] All honorably-discharged veterans in the Grand Army of the Republic and the United Confederate Veterans were invited, and veterans from 46 of the 48 states attended (all except Nevada and Wyoming).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Despite official concerns "that there might be unpleasant differences, at least, between the blue and gray" (as after England's War of the Roses and the French Revolution), the peaceful reunion was characterized by instances of Union–Confederate camaraderie.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] After a number of smaller Gettysburg reunions, including the 1906 Philadelphia Brigade-Pickett's Division reunion during which Brigadier General Lewis Armistead's captured sword was returned to the South, in April 1908 General Henry S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Huidekoper of Philadelphia suggested a 1913 50th anniversary reunion to Pennsylvania Governor Edwin Sydney Stuart.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On September 8, the Gettysburg National Park Commission met with Gettysburg borough officials about the event.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Stuart held a sub-committee meeting on October 25, and addressed the General Assembly about the matter in January 1909.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On May 13, 1909, the Pennsylvania Assembly created the Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg Commission.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission's "first tentative programme" of October 13, 1910 included a "Peace Jubilee", with a noon July 3 placement of the cornerstone for a "Great Peace Memorial".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The August 26, 1912, US Congress bill appropriated $150,000 and directed the War Department to establish the camp.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Because the memorial funding was not approved, the Peace Jubilee plans were removed from the schedule.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The site of the camp and the 8 acres (3.2 ha) for the Great Tent, west of the Codori House, were selected in 1912 and mapped by the Gettysburg National Park Commission.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission also painted avenue fencing, gun carriages, iron tablets, pyramids, and shells from 1912 through June 30, 1913.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On April 13, 1913, the Pennsylvania commission completed the Pennsylvania State Memorial and mailed invitations to 40,000 veterans.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On June 28, President Woodrow Wilson notified the Pennsylvania commission that he would attend the reunion for a "very limited period".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The 33 contributing states provided a total of $1,033,000 for the reunion, with $450,000 coming from Pennsylvania.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania commission headquarters at Gettysburg was at 231 Baltimore Street, with the Harrisburg office of the Secretary (later nicknamed the "Duke of Gettysburg") in Pennsylvania State Capitol's Room 509.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Commemorative tokens and programs were designed for attendees, including three types of Pennsylvania badges ("Press", "Guest", and "Scout"), a commemorative medal, and a souvenir program of poems by attending "Veteran Scout" Jack Crawford.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania Railroad added "a telephone line between Gettysburg and Hanover along the Western Maryland Railway, over which the Pennsy [would] operate a large number of trains during the battle anniversary".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On the Chambersburg-Gettysburg turnpike and the Gettysburg-Petersburg turnpike, tolls ended for the reunion.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the 1911 Sproul Roads Act on June 27, enabling the Commonwealth to acquire private toll roads and make them free for the public.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Water wells were being drilled for the July encampment by February 1, 1913, and hotels in Hanover, Chambersburg, Hagerstown, and "the Blue Ridge section [were] filling rapidly" by June 26.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The War Department's Great Camp (Gettysburg Encampment, Anniversary Camp, or Veterans Camp) provided tents and support facilities for the Civil War veterans and extended from both sides of Long Lane on the north to within 500 yd (460 m) of the Bliss House.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Post Office; 90 Pennsylvania Health Department latrines throughout the camp, with a seating capacity of 3,476; and (near the Great Tent) an emergency station and two health-department Comfort Houses which supplied the Great Tent water fountains.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania commission set up a temporary morgue in the camp.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A special platform on the Round Top Branch was built for veterans to disembark from steam trains into the camp; in February, trolleys of the Gettysburg Electric Railway had been prohibited from using the branch.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The department set up a field hospital on the Kurtz property facing Brickyard Lane on the north foot of East Cemetery Hill and six comfort stations in the borough: one at each railroad station.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The department tested borough wells and mitigated contamination sources upstream from the water-works supply on Marsh Creek.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The American Red Cross Society and 72 additional Boy Scouts operated fourteen 7 ft × 7 ft (2.1 m × 2.1 m) relief stations for first aid and rest on the battlefield-park roads.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Gettysburg's Tuberculosis Dispensary was also used as a relief station.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Attached to the Great Camp were a battery of the Third United States Field Artillery and several companies of regular infantry.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Companies A-D (14 officers and 285 men) of the Fifteenth United States Cavalry arrived on June 26 to guard the battlefield, camping west of Seminary Ridge on the Hagerstown Road.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A "model Camp" for a Pennsylvania cavalry squadron was on the "College Athletic Field" adjoining the commission's headquarters.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A total of 527 people were quartered at the Lutheran Theological Seminary at Gettysburg and Pennsylvania College (renamed Gettysburg College in 1921), including the Pennsylvania Gettysburg Commission, four troops of the Pennsylvania State Police, and (in tents) Governor Tener's staff.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission planned a four-day series of events, with each day dedicated to a different group.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Anticipating that some veterans might arrive early (especially those traveling a long distance), the Great Camp was opened for supper on June 29.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Pennsylvania veterans who attended the state reunion, which adjourned on June 28, made up most of the over 21,000 arrivals that day.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Other veterans arriving early included two Confederate veterans of Culp's Hill, who arrived on June 26.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Captain McCaskey of the Quartermasters Corps had estimated that 6,000 men might arrive on June 29, and temporarily struggled with shortages of food and supplies.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Some veterans left without staying another night.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On June 30, the 1912 base of the Virginia Monument was dedicated; the rest of the monument was completed later.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] At night, a "Union raid" on the Confederate side of the Great Camp was followed by joint parades and campfires.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] ; eight senators, and 21 congressmen were among the officials who arrived that day.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] at 9 p.m. included "gigantic set pieces covering the entire face and crest of Little Round Top".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] ; eight statues had been installed in April.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Woodrow Wilson arrived at 11 a.m. in a special rail car, traveled through the borough, and entered the Great Tent through two rows of Boy Scouts.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] He addressed the audience in the Big Tent about national unity, and left the camp after the National Anthem was played.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] At noon, a five-minute tribute was held in silence for "Our Heroic Dead"; people throughout the area stood at attention, including at the "College Hotel" and "Seminary Hotel".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The tribute began with a bugle salute while the Gettysburg bells in the distance tolled.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The remaining minutes of silence were punctuated by periodic artillery firing in the distance.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] From 5 a.m. to 11 p.m., 7,147 automobiles used the national-park roads as visitors departed.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] About 12,000 veterans had already left on July 2, and about the same number on July 3.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] During the evening of July 2 at the Hotel Gettysburg.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Henry (a Southerner living in Philadelphia) uttered a "vile epithet" about President Abraham Lincoln and caused an argument at his table.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A Union man threw his drink at Henry, who stabbed and slashed men at the table and on his way out to the street before he was apprehended.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Virginia governor spoke to officials on behalf of Henry, and his father (a Confederate major) posted bail for his son.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The victims (all but one of whom were taken to a hospital) were all expected to recover, and most were released from the hospital the next day.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Dismantling of the Great Camp began immediately after the July 4 tribute.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The hospital closed on July 5, and the last veteran left on July 8.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The annual military instructional camp (250 college students) used several tents in the veterans' camp at the "Meadeboro" camp (Newspaper Row) from July 7 to August 15.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The quartermaster headquarters on Baltimore Street closed on August 13, and by August 15 the Grand Camp had been removed except for "four great water storage reservoirs".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A film, *United at Gettysburg*, documented the reunion and was shown at local theaters.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Beitler, Secretary of the Commission, finished compiling the organizations' reports on December 31, 1913.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1913-gettysburg-reunion] To commemorate the reunion, a colonial portico was opened in May 1914 at the seminary's Old Dorm; only the concrete base remains.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 6, 1928.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In a landslide victory, the Republican ticket of Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover and Senator Charles Curtis defeated the Democratic ticket of New York Governor Al Smith and Senator Joseph T.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] After President Calvin Coolidge declined to seek reelection, Hoover emerged as the Republican Party's frontrunner.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] As Hoover's party opponents failed to unite around a candidate, Hoover received a large majority of the vote at the 1928 Republican National Convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The strong state of the economy discouraged some Democrats from running, and Smith was nominated on the first ballot of the 1928 Democratic National Convention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover and Smith had been widely known as potential presidential candidates long before the 1928 campaign, and both were generally regarded as outstanding leaders.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Both were newcomers to the presidential race and presented in their person and record an appeal of unknown potency to the electorate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Both faced serious discontent within their respective parties' membership, and both lacked the wholehearted support of their parties' organization.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Republicans were identified with the booming economy of the 1920s, and Smith, a Roman Catholic, suffered politically from anti-Catholic sentiment particularly in the Solid South, his opposition to Prohibition, and his association with the legacy of corruption by Tammany Hall.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won a third straight Republican landslide and made substantial inroads in the traditionally-Democratic Solid South by winning several states that had not voted for a Republican since the end of Reconstruction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith carried the five states of the Deep South, his running mate's home state of Arkansas, and the Northeastern states of Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover's victory made him the first president born west of the Mississippi River, and he remains the most recent Cabinet secretary to win a presidential election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Curtis became the first (and thus far the only) Native American vice president, and the first vice president with acknowledged non-European ancestry.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last Republican presidential victory until 1952.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] With President Calvin Coolidge choosing not to seek re-election, the race for the nomination was wide open.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The leading candidates were Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover, former Illinois Governor Frank Orren Lowden and Senate Majority Leader Charles Curtis.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] A movement to draft Coolidge failed to gain traction with party insiders or even persuade Coolidge himself.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the few primaries that mattered, Hoover did not perform as well as expected, leaving him with fewer than half the number of pledged delegates that he needed to win the nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Lowden in turn only had half the number of delegates that Hoover did, leaving it looking unlikely that the first rounds of voting would produce a majority for any candidate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Attempts were made to sound out Coolidge and Vice President Charles G.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Dawes as to whether they would be willing to enter the race and break a potential deadlock between Hoover and Lowden, but both Coolidge and Dawes remained aloof.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The matter was unexpectedly resolved when the convention voted to adopt a platform that repudiated the McNary–Haugen Farm Relief Bill, in turn causing Lowden to withdraw his candidacy in protest, and leaving no obvious challenger to Hoover.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The only real competition that remained came from Senator Curtis, whose campaign was left with far too little time to win over the Lowden supporters.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican Convention was held in Kansas City, Missouri from June 12 to 15 and nominated Hoover on the first ballot.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] To attract votes from farmers who were concerned about Hoover's pro-business orientation, the nomination was instead offered to Curtis.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] He accepted and was nominated overwhelmingly on the first ballot.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Curtis was the first candidate of Native American ancestry nominated by a major party for national office.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In his acceptance speech eight weeks after the convention ended, Hoover said: "We in America today are nearer to the final triumph over poverty than ever before in the history of this land...
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] We shall soon with the help of God be in sight of the day when poverty will be banished from this land." That sentence would haunt Hoover during the Great Depression.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Owing to the economic prosperity in the country and rapidly fading public memory of the Teapot Dome scandal, the Democratic Party's prospects looked dim.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] New York Governor Al Smith had previously made two attempts to secure the Democratic nomination.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The 1928 Democratic National Convention was held in Houston, Texas, on June 26 to 28, and Smith became the candidate on the first ballot.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The leadership asked the delegates to nominate Senator Joseph Taylor Robinson of Arkansas, in many ways Smith's political polar opposite, to be his running mate, and Robinson was nominated for vice-president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith was the first Roman Catholic to gain a major party's nomination for president, and his religion became an issue during the campaign.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Many Protestants feared that Smith would take orders from church leaders in the Vatican in making decisions affecting the country.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in the Finnish Socialist Hall in New York City, the eighth Socialist Party Convention met on the thirteenth of April.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] James Maurer, a former State Representative, President of the Pennsylvania Federation of Labor and then Councilman for the city of Reading, was widely considered the frontrunner in the months before the convention met.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] For his boomers however, Maurer stood that his duties as councilman precluded the possibility of any national tour that would be required of his nomination for the presidency, and this declination was made definitive on the tenth of April.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Norman Thomas, a Presbyterian minister who had been one of Maurer's boomers and had himself made it known that he was not a candidate for the Socialist nomination rather swiftly became the new frontrunner, and plans were made for a draft effort.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas and Maurer were nominated unanimously for president and vice president respectively, with both men accepting their nominations.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The only trouble arose on the question of Prohibition, where there remained a split in the party between those who supported the Eighteenth Amendment and those, like Convention Chair Victor Berger, who preferred that it be handled on a state-by-state basis.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the end it was agreed that the party remain silent on the issue of Prohibition.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in the Mecca Temple in New York City, the second Workers Party Convention met on the twenty-fifth of May.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Jay Lovestone served as the convention's keynote speaker, denouncing the Democratic, Republican and Socialist Parties and claiming that the Communists would turn the next "imperialist war" into a civil war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Party Chair William Foster was named as the party's candidate for the presidency while Benjamin Gitlow, a former opponent of Foster's within the party, was named as its candidate for vice president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Scott Nearing was also considered a possible contender for either position on ticket.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in New York City, the tenth Socialist Labor Party Convention met on the twelfth of May.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] With their standard-bearer having passed, the executive committee of the party tendered the presidential nomination to Reynolds, with the place of vice presidential nominee being filled by Jeremiah Crowley of New York.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Speaking of the "decay of the Capitalistic System", Reynolds campaigned on the idea of Industrial democracy.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held at the La Salle Hotel in Chicago, the fifteenth Prohibition Party Convention met on the tenth of July.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Leigh Colvin and other Prohibitionists had found both the Republican and Democratic planks regarding Prohibition as unsatisfactory, and there was open discussion of nominating a ticket despite the continued reversals the party had suffered since 1920.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Those opposed to Hoover rallied on the second ballot however behind frontrunner William Varnery, an insurance salesman and party regular from New York.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] James Edgerton, a Virginian native who had headed the Jefferson-Lincoln League in the failed effort to fuse the Prohibition and Farmer-Labor Parties, was nominated for the vice presidency.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, there remained a concerted effort to withdraw the ticket from the race, resulting in a meeting by the Party National Executive Committee on whether Varney should drop out.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Varney himself was opposed to this plan, and in a narrow vote, four to three, the effort to effectively endorse Hoover for the presidency failed.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in Chicago, the third Farmer-Labor Party Convention met on the tenth of July.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] To run alongside Norris the party had named William J.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Vereen of Georgia, a cotton textile manufacturer, but refused to consider his nomination under any circumstances once the press had brought it to his attention.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Alexander of North Carolina was then nominated in Reed's stead, but on September 18 Alexander requested that his name be withdrawn from the ticket and he later endorsed Al Smith for the presidency.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] At some point after LeRoy Tillman, a nephew of the late Senator Benjamin Tillman of South Carolina, was nominated in Alexander's stead.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Catholicism was a significant burden for Smith's campaign.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Protestant ministers warned that he would take orders from the Pope, whom many Americans sincerely believed would move to the United States to rule the country from a fortress in Washington, DC.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] An example was a statement issued in September 1928 by the National Lutheran Editors' and Managers' Association that opposed Smith's election.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Groups circulated a million copies of a counterfeit oath, claiming that fourth-degree Knights of Columbus members swore to exterminate Freemasons and Protestants and to commit violence against anyone if the church ordered.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith's opposition to Prohibition, a key reform promoted by Protestants, also lost him votes, as did his association with Tammany Hall.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Because many anti-Catholics used the issues to cover for their religious prejudices, Smith's campaign had difficulty denouncing anti-Catholicism as bigotry without offending others who favored Prohibition or disliked Tammany corruption.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Contemporary Prohibition activists said that their main problem with the Democratic candidate was his faith and not any political view.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Bob Jones Sr., a prominent Protestant pastor in South Carolina, said: "I'll tell you, brother, that the big issue we've got to face ain't the liquor question.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] I'd rather see a saloon on every corner of the South than see the foreigners elect Al Smith president".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] A Methodist newspaper in Georgia called Catholicism "a degenerate type of Christianity," while Southern Baptist churches ordered their followers to vote against Smith, claiming that he would close down Protestant churches, end freedom of worship and prohibit reading the Bible.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Hillman Fountain, a Protestant writer, insisted that Catholics should be barred from holding any office.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Farris states that "More disturbing than the ridiculous and the dangerous was the respectable anti-Catholicism", as contemporary newspapers and Protestant churches tried to mask their anti-Catholicism as genuine concern.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Protestant activists insisted that Catholicism represented an alien culture and medieval mentality, claiming that Catholicism was incompatible with American democracy and institutions.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Catholics were portrayed as reactionary despite being more left-wing than mainstream American Protestant congregations at the time.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Those issues made Smith lose several states of the Solid South that had been carried by Democrats since Reconstruction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] This overcame opposition to Smith's campaign in areas with large nonvoting black populations.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Bilbo claimed that Hoover had met with a black member of the Republican National Committee and danced with her.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover's campaign quickly denied the "untruthful and ignoble assertion".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The total vote exceeded that of 1924 by nearly eight million, which was nearly twice the vote cast in 1916 and nearly three times that of 1896.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Every section in the Union increased its vote although the Mountain, East South Central and West South Central States did so least of all.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The greatest increases were in the heavily populated (Northeastern) Mid-Atlantic and East North Central States, where more than 4,250,000 more votes were cast, more than half of the nationwide increase.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] There was an increase of over a million each in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Much of the increase could be attributed to women voting in ever increasing numbers since gaining the national vote in 1920.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won 200 counties in the Southern United States while Smith won 122 traditionally Republican counties in the Northern United States, with 77 of those counties being majority Catholic.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Harding had won in all twelve cities with populations above 500,000 in the 1920 election, but Smith won in Cleveland, Milwaukee, New York City, San Francisco, and St.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Louis, and lost in Baltimore and Pittsburgh by less than 10,000 votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won in the traditionally Democratic Birmingham, Dallas, and Houston.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith was the first Democratic nominee in the 20th century to win a majority of the twelve largest cities in the country.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The net vote totals in the twelve largest cities shifted from Republican to Democratic with Harding having won by 1,540,000 in 1920, Coolidge by 1,308,000 in 1924, while Smith won by 210,000.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Samuel Lubell wrote in *The Future of American Politics* that Franklin D.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's victory in the 1932 election was preceded by Smith's increased vote totals in urban areas.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith's results in the cities in the election improved upon John W.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the boroughs of New York City the vote percentages rose from 33.6% to 67.7% in The Bronx, 39.6% to 60.8% in Manhattan, 31.9% to 59.5% in Brooklyn, 31% to 53.4% in Queens, and 42% to 53.4% in Staten Island.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] He improved in all of those cities from James M.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won the election by a wide margin on pledges to continue the economic boom of the Coolidge years.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] He received more votes than any previous candidate of the Republican Party in every state except five: Rhode Island, Iowa, North Dakota, South Carolina, and Tennessee.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Hoover vote was greater than the Coolidge vote in 2,932 counties; it was less in 143 of the comparable counties.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The 21,400,000 votes cast for Hoover also touched the high-water mark for all votes for a presidential candidate until then and were an increase of more than 5,500,000 over the Coolidge vote four years earlier.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican ticket made substantial inroads in the South: the heaviest Democratic losses were in the three Southern sections (South Atlantic, East South Central, West South Central).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, eight counties recorded more votes cast for "anti-Smith" electors than either major-party candidate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The eleven states of the former Confederacy provided 7.48% of Hoover's votes, with him taking 47.41% of the vote in that region.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] This was the best showing for a Republican in that region at that point in time.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral votes of North Carolina and Virginia had not been awarded to a Republican since 1872, and Florida had not been carried by a Republican since the heavily disputed election of 1876.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Texas was carried by a Republican for the first time in its history, which left Georgia as the only remaining state never carried by a Republican presidential candidate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia would not be won by a Republican until 1964, when Barry Goldwater carried the state.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith also carried staunchly Democratic Alabama by barely 7,000 votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In all, Smith carried only six of the eleven states of the former Confederacy, the fewest carried by a Democratic candidate since the end of Reconstruction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith polled more votes than had any previous Democratic candidate in 30 of the 48 states, all but Alabama, Colorado, Delaware, Idaho, Kansas, Kentucky, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Oregon, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Virginia, and Washington.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In only four of them (Tennessee, Oklahoma, Texas, and New Mexico) did Smith receive fewer votes than Davis had in 1924.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Allan Lichtman notes that since the sole defining issue of the election was anti-Catholicism, it radically realigned states' voting patterns.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover carried Texas, Florida, North Carolina, and Virginia — none of which had backed a post-Reconstruction Republican, while Smith carried historically-Republican Massachusetts and Rhode Island despite the national Republican landslide.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Smith became the first Democrat to ever win a majority of the vote in Massachusetts, and the first since 1852 to win a majority in Rhode Island.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Lichtman further proves this by pointing out that Smith and Hoover had very similar political views save for religion and Prohibition, and yet the 1928 election had a turnout of 57%, despite previous 1920s American elections having their turnouts below 50%.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith received nearly as many votes as Coolidge had in 1924, and his vote exceeded Davis's by more than 6,500,000.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic vote was greater than in 1924 in 2080 counties and fell in 997 counties.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In only one section did the Democratic vote drop below 38%, the Pacific, which was the only one in which the Republican vote exceeded 60%.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democrats made gains in five sections; of those counties, fourteen had never been Democratic and seven had been Democratic only once.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The size and the nature of the distribution of the Democratic vote illustrated Smith's strengths and weaknesses as a candidate.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Despite evidence of an increased Democratic vote, Smith's overwhelming defeat in the electoral college and the retention of so few Democratic counties reflected Hoover's greater appeal.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith won the electoral votes of only the Deep South of the Democratic Solid South, Robinson's home state of Arkansas, and the New England states of Massachusetts and Rhode Island, both of which had a large proportion of Catholic voters.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] His 87 electoral votes were the fewest that a Democratic candidate had won since the 80 votes earned by Horatio Seymour in 1868.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover even carried Smith's home state of New York by a narrow margin.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith carried 914 counties, the fewest in the Fourth Party System.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican total leaped to 2,174 counties, a larger number than even the 1920 landslide.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Third-party support sank almost to the vanishing point, as the election of 1928 proved to be a two-party contest to a greater extent than any other in the Fourth Party System.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Until the major split before the 1948 election in the Democratic Party between Southern Democrats and the more liberal Northern faction, no further significant third-party candidacies as seen in 1912 and 1924 were to occur.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] All "other" votes totaled only 1.08 percent of the national popular vote.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Socialist vote sank to 267,478, and in seven states, there were no Socialist votes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The **1938 Gettysburg reunion** was an encampment of American Civil War veterans on the Gettysburg Battlefield for the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The gathering included approximately 25 veterans of the battle with a further 1,359 Federal and 486 Confederate attendees out of the 8,000 living veterans of the war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Transportation, quarters, and subsistence was federally funded for each veteran and their accompanying attendant.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] If an attendant was needed it was provided.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Roosevelt's July 3 reunion address preceded the unveiling of the Eternal Light Peace Memorial; a newsreel with part of the address was included in the Westinghouse Time Capsule for the 1939 New York World's Fair.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The reunion's support personnel included 19 officers and 250 enlisted men of the Pennsylvania National Guard, and there were 3,185 United States Army personnel in total.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] A "regular army camp" that displayed modern weapons was east of the northward tracks of the Reading Railroad to the Gettysburg College buildings, while the Third Corps headquarters tent was south of Gettysburg near The Angle.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] There were 548 police; from the Pennsylvania State Police and officers from New York City, Philadelphia, and Pittsburgh; and a Gettysburg College building was the "base hospital" under the First Regular Army Medical Regiment.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] To raise reunion funds, in June 1936 Congress authorized 50,000 US Mint commemorative half dollars.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The Battle of Gettysburg half dollar was dated 1936 despite being struck in 1937.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Sculptor Frank Vittor had used Union veteran James Power Stanley of the Battles of the Wilderness, Cold Harbor, North Anna, and Spotsylvania for the model, A special US postage stamp was also advocated for the reunion's opening day.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] hours was between the reviewing stand in the college stadium and the intersection of the Baltimore Pike and the Emmitsburg Road, through the Lincoln Square; and included three groups: distinguished visitors first, followed by U.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Army units and equipment, and more than 50 drum and bugle corps.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] concert was held in the Gettysburg College stadium (the only remaining Jewish Civil War veteran, Daniel Harris, was a guest on the platform).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/1938-gettysburg-reunion] at dusk, and searchlights were directed from the ground at the planes while they dropped flares.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Even before secession, the governor of Alabama Andrew B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Moore defied the United States government by seizing the two federal forts at the Gulf Coast (forts Morgan and Gaines) and the arsenal at Mount Vernon in January 1861 to distribute weapons to Alabama towns.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The peaceful seizure of Alabama forts preceded by three months the bombing and capture of the Union's Fort Sumter (SC) on April 12, 1861.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Alabama was politically divided, voting to secede 61–39%, with most opposition by Unionists in northern Alabama.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Citizens would subsequently join Confederate forces, with some Alabamians joining Union forces.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Issues of slavery also were divided, with emancipation denied, but slaves protected, allowed trial by jury same as free whites, and African Slave Trade was discouraged in the 1861 Ordinances.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Alabama provided a significant source of troops and leaders, military material, supplies, food, horses and mules.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Alabama Secession Convention invited delegates from the fourteen slaveholding states to join at Montgomery, on February 11, 1861, when seven Cotton States of the Lower South formed the new republic, with Montgomery as Confederate capital and former Mississippi U.S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Senator Jefferson Davis as President of the Confederacy.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Hale, Alabama's commissioner to Kentucky, wrote a letter to that state's governor about Alabama's justification for secession.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Hale, letter to the Governor of Kentucky (December 1860).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] — speaking to the Alabama Secession Convention (January 25, 1861).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In an 1861 speech delivered by Alabama politician Robert Hardy Smith, he said that the state of Alabama had left the United States over the issue of slavery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] — Robert Hardy Smith, An Address to the Citizens of Alabama on the Constitution and Laws of the Confederate States of America (1861).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The 1861 Alabama Constitution Ordinance 20 (approved January 28, 1861) insisted the planned Confederacy oppose what it called the "African Slave Trade" and not consider to re-open the issue.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Newspapers in Alabama also supported secession to preserve slavery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] According to one newspaper in Montgomery, slavery was a benevolent "religious institution" allowing care of slaves who might perish in other regions.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Upon its secession Alabama adopted a new state constitution.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] — Article IV, Section 1, Constitution of the State of Alabama (1861).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Moore energetically supported the Confederate war effort.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Even before hostilities began in April 1861, he seized U.S. forts on the Alabama Gulf Coast (Morgan and Gaines) and the arsenal in Mount Vernon, in January 1861, sent agents to buy rifles in the Northeast, and scoured the state for weapons.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Despite strong resistance in the northern part of the state, Alabama seceded by vote 61–39 and formed the Confederate States of America.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Cobb, a Unionist, pleaded for compromise.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] He ran for Congress, but was soundly defeated (he was subsequently elected in 1863 on a wave of anti-war sentiment, with war-weariness growing in Alabama).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The new nation brushed Cobb aside and set up its provisional capital in Montgomery and selected Jefferson Davis as president.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In May the Confederate government left Montgomery before the sickly season began and relocated to Richmond, Virginia, after Virginia had seceded in April 1861.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] From his plantation on the river, he took a steamboat up the Mississippi to Vicksburg, boarded a train to Jackson, where he took another train north to Grand Junction, then a third train east to Chattanooga, Tennessee, and a fourth train southeast to Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Yet another train took Davis west, back to the Alabama border, where a final train took him to Montgomery.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] He was in a hurry, but it took five days.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] A few months later in April 1861, the Fall of Fort Sumter took place.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] This event resulted in four more southern slave holding states, Virginia, Arkansas, Tennessee, and North Carolina, to secede from the Union and join the Confederacy and its war effort.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Fall of Fort Sumter also marked the beginning of fighting in the American Civil War.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] As the war proceeded, internal transportation became much more difficult.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Union seized the Tennessee and Mississippi rivers, burned trestles and railroad bridges, and tore up track; the frail Confederate railroad system faltered and virtually collapsed for want of repairs and replacement parts.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] For example, The Mobile and Ohio Railroad connected the main port at Mobile to points north, ending in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Historian James Doster reports that when the war ended, "Only a fourth of the rolling stock remained, and that was in bad condition.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The 184-mile roadway from Okolona to Union City was damaged by decay and destruction of bridges, trestlework, crossties, and water stations".
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The port of Mobile was blockaded by the U.S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Navy, but some small, fast blockade runners got through at first, carrying out cotton and bringing in luxuries, food and munitions.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] At the outbreak of war, the state's economy was weak; during the war it declined further.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Before the war, most people worked in agriculture.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The largest industry was the railroads, followed by gristmills then sawmills.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Perhaps 17% of the state's White population was in military service, but this was skewed to a much larger percentage of the economically valuable young men.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The full crops planted in 1861 were harvested by those left behind, but the 1862 planting was smaller.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Further, many counties suffered a drought in 1862, which further reduced harvest production.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In Coosa County, corn production was down by 150,000 bushels from 1861.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Twenty counties (of 67) were unable to produce any surplus of corn.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] This brought hunger to families left behind by many Confederate soldiers.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Wartime conditions made it difficult to move food from areas of surplus to those that were suffering.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Poverty became widespread as shortages drove up food prices.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] During the war, the legislature provided almost twelve million dollars in poverty relief funds.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] However, as the state government alleviated these needs by printing paper money not backed by any assets, the resulting massive inflation only made economic hardship worse.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In 1861, the state recorded 7% of White families as indigent.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In 1862 the figure was 34%, it rose to 39% the following year.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Harsh conditions at home encouraged many soldiers to desert.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] A November 1864 list shows some 7,994 men had left their units.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Later, bread riots hit Mobile in both April and September 1863.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] By 1864, roving bands of "corn women" wandered the state begging and stealing.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Due to the naval blockade of southern ports, salt began to be in short supply.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The State of Alabama constructed salt works in Clarke County to harvest salt from the local salt springs.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The salt was shipped to Mississippi, Georgia, and used in Alabama by the military and civilians.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] About 10,000 slaves escaped and joined the Union Army, along with 2,700 white Alabamian men who joined Union forces.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The state raised five regiments for the U.S.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Army, four of them Black regiments of the United States Colored Troops.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] On the opposing side, there were Confederate troops in sixty-five infantry regiments, plus sixteen cavalry and three of artillery that fought for the Confederacy.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] A large number of irregular and militia units were also organized locally.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Alabama was shielded by geography and Confederate troops against most major military operations, except the Battle of Mobile Bay (August 1864) and final conflicts of the War at Spanish Fort and Fort Blakeley (April 9, 1865), the last major battle of the Civil War.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The state contributed about 120,000 Confederate troops, nearly all the white population capable of bearing arms.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Most were recruited locally and served with men they knew, which built esprit and strengthened ties to home.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Medical conditions were severe; about 15% of Alabama's Confederate forces died of disease, and 10% from battle.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Alabama had few well-equipped hospitals, but it had many women who volunteered to nurse the sick and wounded.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Soldiers were poorly equipped, especially after 1863, and often resorted to pillaging the dead for boots, belts, canteens, blankets, hats, shirts and pants.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Thousands of slaves performed forced labor for the Confederate side; they took care of horses and equipment, cooked and did laundry, hauled supplies, and helped in field hospitals.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Many slaves were tasked with building defensive installations, especially around Mobile, with at least five hundred dying from harsh working conditions.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] They graded roads, repaired railroads, drove supply wagons, and labored in iron mines, iron foundries and even in the munitions factories.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] As they were enslaved, their labor was involuntary, their unpaid labor was forcibly impressed from the slaveholders, many of whom resented having their slaves assigned to the war effort.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Thirty-nine Alabamians attained the ranks of general or admiral, most notably Admiral Raphael Semmes.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Josiah Gorgas was the Chief of Ordnance for the Confederacy.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] He located new munitions plants in Selma that employed 10,000 workers until Union raiders in 1865 burned down the factories.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Selma Arsenal made most of the Confederacy's ammunition.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Selma Naval Ordnance Works manufactured artillery, turning out a cannon every five days.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Confederate Naval Yard built ships and was noted for launching the CSS *Tennessee* in 1863 to defend Mobile Bay.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Selma's Confederate Nitre Works procured niter for gunpowder from limestone caves.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] When supplies were low, it advertised for housewives to save the contents of their chamber pots, as urine was a rich source of organic nitrogen.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The state's losses at Gettysburg were 1,750 dead plus even more captured or wounded; the famed "Alabama Brigade" took 781 casualties.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In 1863 Federal forces secured a foothold in northern Alabama in spite of spirited opposition from Confederate cavalry under General Nathan B.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] A notable Confederate officer from Alabama was Col.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] He was an instrumental commander during the attack at Little Round Top during the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] From 1861 the Union blockade shut Mobile Bay, and in August 1864 the outer defenses of Mobile were taken by a Federal fleet during the Battle of Mobile Bay.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] On April 12, 1865, three days after the surrender of Robert E.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Lee at Appomattox Courthouse, the city of Mobile surrendered to the Union army to avoid destruction following the Union victories at the Battle of Spanish Fort and the Battle of Fort Blakeley.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Magee Farm, north of Mobile, was the site of preliminary arrangements for the surrender of the last Confederate States Army east of the Mississippi River.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Confederate General Richard Taylor negotiated a ceasefire with Union General Edward Canby at the house on April 29, 1865.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Taylor's forces comprised 47,000 Confederate troops serving in Alabama, Mississippi and Louisiana.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] There was a small loyalist element in northern Alabama that needed Union military support to survive.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] On the one hand, with Union troops present, Southern Unionists were finally able to come out of hiding, join the Union Army if desired, and care for their families, who were now protected from Confederate partisans.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] On the other hand, Union troops doubled the amount of regional foraging compared to the Confederates.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Federal foragers in Northern Alabama were, for the most part, an adventurous group that were aided by loyal Unionists, and they took all they needed for their vast forces, often raiding farms and homes previously struck by the Confederates.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Before the arrival of Federal troops, local Unionist resistance networks were based on underground cells that aided pro-Union Loyalists by means of finances, contacts, supplies, and much needed local intelligence.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Recruits from Alabama who had joined Union regiments used their familiarity with the social network and physical geography of the homefront to locate, rescue, and recruit beleaguered Unionists still behind Confederate lines.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Loyalists were given assurance of safety and a job if they were to give the U.S. forces supplies, information, contacts, and money.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Some Loyalists were drafted, and some were volunteers.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] White Unionists used the army as a tool to defeat the forces threatening to destroy the old Union, and their families and neighborhoods along with it.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The most well-known unit composed entirely of Alabama Unionists was the 1st Alabama Cavalry Regiment (Union).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Of the 2,678 white Alabamians who enlisted in the Union Army, 2,066 served in it.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Union partisans were motivated by a sense of duty and obligation to the Union cause and a need to protect their family and Unionist friends.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] They were also motivated by a desire for vengeance for all the wrongs they had suffered at Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Unionist guerrilla bands were typically fairly compact, numbering between twenty and a hundred men.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] They were independently organized, but were loosely associated and actively supported by occupying Union forces.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Their missions included acting as spies, guides, scouts, recruiters behind enemy lines, and anti-guerrilla fighters to protect Union forces and infrastructure.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Navy's blockade shut down exports, it blocked essential imports, except with blockade runners.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] They cut back on purchases, brought out old spinning wheels and enlarged their gardens with peas and peanuts to provide clothing and food.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] They used ersatz substitutes when possible, but there was no real coffee, and it was hard to develop a taste for the okra or chicory substitutes used.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The households were severely hurt by inflation in the cost of everyday items and the shortages of food, fodder for the animals, and medical supplies for the wounded.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Women had to manage the estates which the men had left behind.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Another role the women played was managing the slaves while their husbands were away at war.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Jonathan Wiener studied the census data on plantations in black-belt counties, 1850–70, and found that the War did not drastically alter the responsibilities and roles of women.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The age of the groom went up as younger women married older planters, and birth rates dropped sharply during 1863-68 during Reconstruction.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] However he finds that plantation mistresses were not more likely to operate plantations than in earlier years, nor was there a lost generation of women without men.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The women of the Alabama Unionists helped with long-distance communication networks, and they were able to move freely from town to town because of their gender.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] When these women lost their Unionist husbands, it was often a struggle to survive, as they were completely ostracized by the pro-Confederate women.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Storey finds that their intense loyalty to kin, neighbors, and nation strengthened the Unionists against Confederate ideological pressures so much that they preferred to abandon the slave system and their high socioeconomic status in order to remain true to the Union.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Storey, "Regardless of the Union's ambivalence toward slaves and slavery, black men and women in Alabama" saw the Union occupation as the surest path to freedom.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Many of the Confederate guerrillas in northern Alabama were detached cavalry units that were used to great advantage in protecting the home front, as opposed to serving in the main army.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The primary mission of the pro-Confederate guerrillas was to attempt to keep intact the Confederate social and political order.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] They assisted the war effort in their own backyards by hunting down and arresting Unionists, conscripts, and deserters.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] In addition, they terrorized Unionists by destroying their property and threatening their families.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Confederate guerillas were made up of four types of fighters–the first half of these were under Confederate supervision, being either detached cavalry or enlisted men fighting close to home.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The other units either fought disguised as noncombatants or were simply outlaws looking for blood-letting opportunities.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] These men were not under Confederate control and were as interested in profit as helping the Southern cause.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Not all Union partisans were confined to the Union-occupied areas of Alabama.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] These renegades sometimes worked with regular U.S. forces based in Pensacola, Florida, and their depredations led several leading citizens of these counties to petition the governor, T.H.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Watts, for military assistance against them.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Some local citizens, such as Methodist minister Bill Sketoe of Newton, were even hanged by Home Guard elements for alleged acts of collaboration with these guerrillas.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The Battle of Columbus, on the Alabama-Georgia border (part of Wilson's Raid, April 16, 1865), is widely regarded as the last battle of the war, being the final engagement before the dissolution of the Confederacy on May 5.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Alabama soldiers fought in hundreds of battles; the state's losses at Gettysburg were 1,750 dead plus even more captured or wounded; the famed "Alabama Brigade" took 781 casualties.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Parsons in July 1865 made a preliminary estimate of losses.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Nearly all the white men had served, some 122,000 he said, of whom 35,000 died in the war and at least another 30,000 were seriously disabled.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Patton estimated that 20,000 veterans had returned home permanently disabled, and there were 20,000 widows and 60,000 orphans.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] With cotton prices low, the value of farms shrank, from $176 million in 1860 to only $64 million in 1870.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The livestock supply shrank too, as the number of horses fell from 127,000 to 80,000, and mules from 111,000 to 76,000.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The overall population of Alabama remained nearly the same, as the growth that might have been expected was neutralized by death and emigration.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Deputies from the first seven states to secede formed the first two sessions of the 1861 Provisional Confederate Congress.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The bicameral First Confederate Congress (1862–64) included two senators from Alabama—Clement Claiborne Clay and William Lowndes Yancey (died July 23, 1863; replaced by Robert Jemison Jr.).
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Representing Alabama in the House of Representatives were Thomas Jefferson Foster, William Russell Smith, John Perkins Ralls, Jabez Lamar Monroe Curry, Francis Strother Lyon, William Parish Chilton Sr., David Clopton, James Lawrence Pugh, and Edmund Strother Dargan.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Alabama's two senators in the Second Confederate Congress (1864–65) were Robert Jemison Jr., and Richard Wilde Walker.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Representatives were Thomas Jefferson Foster, William Russell Smith, Marcus Henderson Cruikshank, Francis Strother Lyon, William Parish Chilton Sr., David Clopton, James L.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] The CSA Congress refused to seat Representative-elect W.R.W.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Cobb because he was an avowed Unionist; therefore his district was not represented.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] War practices were controversial, with land mines at Fort Blakeley exploding on Union troops even after the battle ended.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Almost immediately after the Confederacy surrendered, there were allegations that some Confederate soldiers were shot by the Union colored troops, however these allegations were never proven.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Available evidence indicates that some Union soldiers may have fired on Confederates who had surrendered but there was no large scale massacre.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Following the end of the Civil War, Alabama was part of the Third Military District.
[src:alabama-in-the-american-civil-war/alabama-in-the-american-civil-war] Northern Alabama voters sided with Republican Party for decades after the Civil War, while central and southern Alabama was part of the Solid South for the Democratic Party.
